This article is a presidential proclamation by Barack Obama declaring January 18, 2010, as Martin Luther King, Jr., Federal Holiday. The proclamation highlights Dr. King's impact on the nation and emphasizes the importance of continuing his work towards equality and justice. It calls for supporting the next generation of leaders, addressing social injustice and poverty, and investing in education. The proclamation also encourages Americans to engage in service and support humanitarian efforts, particularly in response to the earthquake in Haiti at the time. Overall, it emphasizes the need to honor Dr. King's legacy and work towards a more equal and just society.